{
  "answer": "**The work is *San Hyan Kamahayanikan* (by Mpu Shri Sambhara Surya Warama), Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis chapter maps the five Tathāgatas to states of the practitioner's breath exactly as described, locating their abodes \"at the tip of the nose, on the forehead, and at the crown of the head\" and calling them both \"the fivefold culmination of stainless purity\" and \"the Five Sacred Tastes.\" The verbatim five-line mapping is:\n\n> * The breath in the right is called Amitābha.  \n> * The breath in the left is called Amoghasiddhi.  \n> * The breath exiting both at once is called Ratnasambhava.  \n> * The breath not exiting from the left or right is called Akṣobhya.  \n> * The culmination of the breath is called Vairocana.[^1]\n\n[^1]: *San Hyan Kamahayanikan*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19/01/translation/#p-cf2520).",
